<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="531" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1286,1599]" box="[151,1436,1286,1311]" pageId="10" pageNumber="531">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1286,1311]" pageId="10" pageNumber="531">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[282,556,1286,1311]" class="Insecta" family="Conopidae" genus="Physocephala" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="531" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegata">
<emphasis box="[282,556,1286,1311]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="531">Physocephala variegata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a unique species belonging to a group which has a broad stripe of pleural
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1286,1599]" box="[151,1437,1322,1347]" pageId="10" pageNumber="531">dusting reaching from the mid coxa all the way up to the notopleuron and not becoming narrower dorsally. It is</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1286,1599]" box="[151,1436,1358,1383]" pageId="10" pageNumber="531">easily distinguished from other European species of this group, and indeed from all other European species, by the</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1286,1599]" box="[151,1436,1394,1419]" pageId="10" pageNumber="531">characteristic broad dusting on the parafacia. The reduced dark wing pattern and the distinct areas without</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1286,1599]" box="[151,898,1430,1455]" pageId="10" pageNumber="531">microtrichia on the wing also distinguish this from similar species.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
